of our Galaxy, we use the given parameters and Newton's law of universal gravitation. 1. **Convert the angular radius to radians**: \[ \theta = 0.12 \text{ arcseconds} \times \frac{1 \text{ arcsecond}}{3600 \text{ arcminutes}} \times \frac{1 \text{ degree}}{180 \text{ arcminutes}} \times \frac{\pi \text{ radians}}{180 \text{ degrees}} \approx 5.8177 \times 10^{-7} \text{ radians} \] 2. **Convert the distance to the Galactic center to meters**: \[ D = 8 \text{ kpc} \times 3.08567758 \times 10^{16} \text{ meters/parsec} \approx 2.4685 \times 10^{20} \text{ meters} \] 3. **Calculate the orbital radius of the star around the black hole**: \[ r = \theta \times D \approx 5.8177 \times 10^{-7} \times 2.4685 \times 10^{20} \approx 1.4389 \times 10^{14} \text{ meters} \] 4. **Convert the orbital period to seconds**: \[ T = 15 \text{ years} \times 365.25 \text{ days/year} \times 24 \text{ hours/day} \times 3600 \text{ seconds/hour} \approx 4.7336 \times 10^8 \text{ seconds} \] 5. **Apply Newton's law of universal gravitation**: \[ M = \frac{4\pi^2}{G} \times \frac{r^3}{T^2} \] Substituting the values: \[ M = \frac{4\pi^2}{6.67430 \times 10^{-11} \text{ m}^3 \text{kg}^{-1} \text{s}^{-2}} \times \frac{(1.4389 \times 10^{14} \text{ meters})^3}{(4.7336 \times 10^8 \text{ seconds})^2} \] Calculating step-by-step: \[ r^3 \approx 2.9784 \times 10^{42} \text{ m}^3, \quad T^2 \approx 2.2382 \times 10^{17} \text{ s}^2 \] \[ \frac{r^3}{T^2} \approx 1.327 \times 10^{25} \text{ m}^3/\text{s}^2 \] \[ \frac{4\pi^2}{G} \approx 39.4784 \text{ kg}^{-1} \text{ m}^3 \text{ s}^{-2} \] \[ M \approx 39.4784 \times 1.327 \times 10^{25} \approx 7.85 \times 10^{35} \text{ kg} \] 6. **Convert the mass to solar masses**: \[ \frac{7.85 \times 10^{35} \text{ kg}}{1.989 \times 10^{30} \text{ kg/solar mass}} \approx 3.94 \times 10^5 \text{ solar masses} \] Rounding to 1 significant figure, the mass of the black hole is \boxed{4 \times 10^5} times the mass of the Sun.
